ce:section.ce:para:
Fluorescent sensing offers a facile approach to detect and differentiate multiple analytes of interest simultaneously [9]. As a result, a variety of molecular fluorophores or fluorescent materials have been utilized as sensing platforms to detect analytes of significance [10]; among which, carbon dots (C-dots) have gained significant attention [11–13] because of their excellent water dispersibility [14], high photoluminescence (PL) intensity [15,16], tunable surface functionality and high photostability [17,18], as well as prominent biocompatibility [19,20]. Recently, numerous assays have been established for the sensing of Fe3+ with C-dots as the platform, leading to fruitful results [12,21–25] (
                        Table S1
                     ). For instance, Wang et al. designed C-dots based assay which achieved an extremely low limit of detection (LOD, 0.06 μM) [21]. In a similar work, Shi et al. established an assay with a wide linear range 0f 0–1000 μM [22]. In another study, Qi et al. demonstrated the practicality of C-dots based assays by achieving the detection of Fe3+ in real water environment [23]. Despite these advancements, simple and convenient assays that could achieve Fe3+ sensing in complex water environment (i.e., lakes) and biological systems (i.e., cells) with high sensitivity and selectivity are still scarce. Furthermore, as far as we are aware, there were very few fluorescent probes based on C-dots that were capable of detecting both Fe3+ and amino acids (
                        Table S1
                     ). Therefore, there is still a significant need to explore the potential of C-dots for building single nano-sensor capable of detecting multiple target analytes (i.e., Fe3+ and amino acids) simultaneously.

Before establishing the calibration curves for Fe3+ sensing, some important parameters including C-dots concentration and response time for the assay development were optimized first. To figure out the best C-dots concentration for the sensing assay development, the emissions of C-dots at various concentrations from 0 to 900 mg/L were obtained and carefully analyzed (
                           Fig. S5
                        ), from which an optimal concentration of 200 mg/L was selected for the subsequent assay development. Then, we also investigated the optimal incubation time for this assay. Specifically, upon the addition of Fe3+ (75 μM) to the C-dots dispersion, C-dots PL was significantly quenched and rapidly reached balance in 3 min (
                           Fig. S6
                        ), highlighting the quick response of this assay. Collectively, C-dots concentration and incubation time were set as 200 mg/L and 3 min, respectively, for the subsequent assay development.
